What’s really going on

When you use an API key, you’re saying:

“I trust this holder to act as me—within these boundaries.”

So every system ends up stacking layers like:
	•	Identity → who are you?
	•	Authentication → prove it
	•	Authorization → what are you allowed to do
	•	Accounting → what did you actually do

API keys mostly sit in:

authentication + authorization (lite version)

⸻

Why there are so many layers

Because no single layer is enough.

Each one covers a different failure mode:
	•	Passwords can be guessed
	•	Keys can be leaked
	•	Tokens can expire
	•	Behavior can drift

So systems evolve into:

layered trust instead of perfect trust

⸻

